etween Indians and the United States Constitution that explains the present state of confusion and inconsistent application in U.S. Indian law. The authors examine all sections of the Constitution that explicitly and implicitly apply to Indians and discuss how they have been interpreted and applied from the early republic up to the present. They convincingly argue that the Constitution does not provide any legal rights for American Indians and that the treaty-making process should govern relations between Indian nations and the federal government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aConstitutional history-United States. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCivil rightsxHistory. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.xHistory. 0aIndians of North America-Civil rights-History. 0aIndians of North America-Legal status, laws, etc.-History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aWilkins, David E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71607040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292749238423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292749238/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK